TY  - JOUR
T1  - On Efficient Solutions to Multiple Objective Mathematical Programs
AU  - Lowe, T. J.
AU  - Thisse, J.-F.
AU  - Ward, J. E.
AU  - Wendell, R. E.
Y1  - 1984/11/01
PY  - 1984
DA  - 1984/11/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.30.11.1346
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.30.11.1346
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 1346
EP  - 1349
VL  - 30
IS  - 11
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - This note develops properties of quasi-efficient solutions and explores interrelationships to the classical concept of efficiency. In particular, a point is a quasi-efficient solution to a multiple objective mathematical program if and only if it is an optimal solution to a scalar maximum problem for some set of nonnegative weights on the objectives. This result is then used to characterize the set of quasi-efficient solutions as the union of efficient solutions to a multiple objective problem over all nonempty subsets of the objectives.
AB  - This note develops properties of quasi-efficient solutions and explores interrelationships to the classical concept of efficiency. In particular, a point is a quasi-efficient solution to a multiple objective mathematical program if and only if it is an optimal solution to a scalar maximum problem for some set of nonnegative weights on the objectives. This result is then used to characterize the set of quasi-efficient solutions as the union of efficient solutions to a multiple objective problem over all nonempty subsets of the objectives.
